==English==

===Etymology===
From {{prefix|en|neo|liberalism}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# A [[political]] [[ideology]] or [[ideological]] [[trend]] based on [[neoclassical]] [[economics]] that espouses [[economic]] [[liberalism]], favouring trade [[liberalisation]], financial [[deregulation]], a small government, [[privatisation]] and liberalisation of government businesses, passive [[antitrust]] enforcement, accepting greater economic [[inequality]] and disfavouring [[unionisation]].
#: {{syn|en|economic rationalism|market liberalism}}
#: {{hypo|en|Reaganomics|Rogernomics|Thatcherism}}
#: {{hyper|en|capitalism}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=November 17, 2016|title=Goodbye, American neoliberalism. A new era is here|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/nov/17/american-neoliberalism-cornel-west-2016-election|author=Cornel West|authorlink=Cornel West|work=The Guardian|passage=The age of Obama was the last gasp of '''neoliberalism'''. Despite some progressive words and symbolic gestures, Obama chose to ignore Wall Street crimes, reject bailouts for homeowners, oversee growing inequality and facilitate war crimes like US drones killing innocent civilians abroad.}}
# {{lb|en|US}} The ideology associated with the [[New Democrat]]s and the {{w|Democratic Leadership Council}}.

